South African Stocks: Gold Fields, Mondi Move in Johannesburg

-- B y   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n
-- 
2011-06-30T08:46:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-30/south-african-stocks-gold-fields-mondi-move-in-johannesburg.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
rose for a fifth day, advancing 38.99, or 0.1 percent, to
31,765.29 by 10:27 a.m. in Johannesburg. The measure has
retreated 1.4 percent this quarter.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , the continent’s second-biggest
producer of the metal, snapped three days of increases, losing
27 cents, or 0.3 percent, to 99.19 rand. Gold fell for the first
time in three days, losing 0.3 percent to $1,508.22 an ounce.  Mondi Ltd. (MND)  ,  Europe ’s largest maker of office
paper, rose for a third day, gaining 35 cents, or 0.6 percent,
to 65.96 rand. Mondi shareholders will vote on whether to
approve separating the group and listing Mondi Packaging South
Africa Ltd. on the stock exchange. If approved, the listing will
take place on July 11.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Lauren van der Westhuizen in Cape Town Nef at 
 lvanderwesth@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
